63:["$","h4","h4-0",{"children":"Biohybrid and Soft Robotics (2025–2026 Breakthroughs)"}]
64:["$","p","p-5",{"children":"The line between biological organism and machine has blurred significantly. Traditional rigid robotics struggle with power-to-weight ratios and safe human interaction. Biohybrid systems solve this by using living biological tissue as actuators (motors) and sensors."}]
65:["$","ul","ul-30",{"children":["\n",["$","li","li-0",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Muscle-Driven Robotics"}],": In March 2026, researchers demonstrated the \"OstraBot\" (",["$","em","em-0",{"children":"Nature Communications"}],"), the fastest skeletal muscle-driven biohybrid robot to date (467 mm/min). The breakthrough involved mechanically coupling lab-grown muscle tissues to \"train\" against each other, drastically increasing force output."]}],"\n",["$","li","li-1",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Living Actuators for Dexterity"}],": In early 2025, ",["$","em","em-0",{"children":"Science Robotics"}]," published the creation of a \"Biohybrid Robot Hand\" actuated by multiple human muscle tissue bundles (MuMuTAs). This hand successfully performed complex, antagonistic gestures like playing Rock, Paper, Scissors."]}],"\n",["$","li","li-2",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Fungal Computing"}],": Moving beyond animal cells, a 2025 Cornell University study demonstrated biohybrid rovers controlled entirely by electrical signals processed from King Oyster mushroom mycelia. Fungal networks provide robust, self-healing, and extremely low-power analog computing arrays for soft robots."]}],"\n"]}]
